Introduction¶

The following project is a fictional case study of a retail company that would like to optimize its pricing strategy based on the provided dataset.

The retail market is extremely competitive. Pricing is a key factor in attracting customers and ensuring a company's success. Several factors influence pricing decisions, including the cost of producing the goods, customer demand, competitor pricing, and the desired profit margin. Companies must carefully consider these factors to determine the most effective pricing strategy. This involves finding a balance between maximizing sales volume and maintaining profitability.

Purpose¶

Leverage the data to develop a data-driven price optimization strategy that maximizes profits.

Questions¶

  • What is the total revenue/units sold per product?
  • What is the total revenue/units sold per category?
  • What is the market share of units sold per category?
  • What is the profit margin of each product compared to other companies
  • What is the average product score of each product/category compared to other companies?

Data¶

The dataset provided, retail_price.csv, was downloaded from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/suddharshan/retail-price-optimization/data, stored locally and is licensed as "CCO: Public Domain". The dataset contains 30 columns and 676 rows.

  • product_id (string) - A unique identifier for each product in the dataset

  • product_category_name (string) - Category for which the product belongs to

  • month_year (date) - data in the format (dd-mm-yyyy) within the range between 01-01-2017 and 01-08-2018. Only months and years are important here.

  • qty (integer) - Number of products sold in a given month

  • total_price (float) - Montly revenue for a given product

  • freight_price (float) - Freight price of the product

  • unit_price (float) - Unit price of the product

  • product_name_length (integer) - Number of characters in the product name

  • product_description_length (integer) - Number of characters in the product description

  • product_photos_qty (integer) - Number of photos available for the product

  • product_weight_g (integer) - Unit weight in grams

  • product_score (float) - User rating for the product

  • customers (integer) - The number of customers who purchased a product in the given category that month (market demand)

  • weekday (integer) - Number of weekdays per month

  • weekend (integer) - Number of weekend days per month

  • holiday (integer) - Number of holidays per month

  • month (integer) - Month which was taken from the 'month_year' column

  • year (integer) - Year which was taken from the 'month_year' column

  • s (float) - The effect of seasonality - The total percentage share of sales during that month compared to annual sales

  • volume (integer) - Unknown parameter - presumed to be total physical volume of the product

  • comp_1, comp_2, comp_3 (float) - Unit price from 3 competitors

  • ps1, ps2, ps3 (float) - Product score or review rating from 3 competitors

  • fp1, fp2, fp3 (float) - Unit freight price from 3 competitors

  • lag_price (float) - Unit price for the previous month

What is the price elasticity for each product category?¶
In [20]:
price_elasticity_values = []
p_value = []

# take the natural logarithm of the price and quantity variables
df['log_price'] = np.log(df['unit_price'])
df['log_quantity'] = np.log(df['qty'])

# run a linear regression of the log-transformed quantity on the log-transformed price for each category
for category in df['product_category_name'].unique():
    category_df = df[df['product_category_name'] == category]
    X = category_df['log_price']
    y = category_df['log_quantity']
    X = sm.add_constant(X)
    model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    elasticity = model.params['log_price']
    price_elasticity_values.append(elasticity)
    p_value.append(model.f_pvalue)


# create a DataFrame for the results
price_elasticity_df = pd.DataFrame({'product_category_name': df['product_category_name'].unique(), 'price_elasticity': price_elasticity_values, 'p_value': p_value})

# print the results
price_elasticity_df.sort_values('price_elasticity', ascending=False)

How to interpret these values?

The price elasticity of a product is a measure of how responsive the quantity demanded is to changes in price. A positive price elasticity means that an increase in price leads to an increase in quantity demanded, while a negative price elasticity means that an increase in price leads to a decrease in quantity demanded. The magnitude of the number represents the strength of the relationship between price and quantity demanded.

Further, we are looking for p_values below 0.05. A p_value less than 0.05 means that the relationship between price and quantity demanded is statistically significant. A p_value greater than 0.05 means that the relationship between price and quantity demanded is not statistically significant and is more likely to be due to random chance.

The bed_bath_table, garden_tools and console_game categories appear to be statistically significant, however, we have multiple products in each category so let's take a closer look at the price elasticity for each product ID

In [21]:
# Initialize empty lists to store results
price_elasticity_values = []
p_value = []
product_ids = []
avg_price_values = []
avg_qty_values = []

# take the natural logarithm of the price and quantity variables
df['log_price'] = np.log(df['unit_price'])
df['log_quantity'] = np.log(df['qty'])

# Loop through each product category
for product in df['product_id'].unique():
    product_df = df[df['product_id'] == product]
    X = product_df['log_price']
    y = product_df['log_quantity']
    X = sm.add_constant(X)
    model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    elasticity = model.params['log_price']
    avg_price = product_df['unit_price'].mean() 
    avg_qty = product_df['qty'].mean()
    p = model.f_pvalue
    
    # Only append results if p-value is below 0.05
    if p < 0.05:
        price_elasticity_values.append(elasticity)
        p_value.append(p)
        product_ids.append(product)
        avg_price_values.append(round(avg_price,2))  
        avg_qty_values.append(round(avg_qty,1)) 

# Create a DataFrame for the results
price_elasticity_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'product_id': product_ids,
    'price_elasticity': price_elasticity_values,
    'p_value': p_value,
    'avg_price': avg_price_values,   
    'avg_qty': avg_qty_values 
})

# Sort the DataFrame by price elasticity in descending order
price_elasticity_df.sort_values('price_elasticity', ascending=False, inplace=True)

# Print the results
price_elasticity_df.reset_index(drop=True)

When looking at health3 for example, a price elasticity of 25.58 would suggest that an increase in price of 1% would lead to an increase in quantity demanded by 25.58%. Whereas with bed4, which has a price elasticity of -29.83, an increase in price of 1% would lead to a decrease in quantity demanded by 29.83%. The opposite is also true, where a decrease in price of 1% would lead to an increase in quantity demanded by 29.83%.

Conclusion¶

Highlights¶

The categories with most market demand are garden_tools, health_beauty and watches_gifts. These categories also represent the highest revenue categories for the company, however, they also represent the lowest market share categories between 13%-15%. Thus, there may be some opportunities to explore further in these categories.

The company has a dominant market share in the console_games and perfumery categories, however, those 2 categories also represent the lowest market demand.

The health_beauty category also has much higher profit margins than the rest. bed_bath_table, computers_accessories and cool_stuff have moderately higer profit margins while furniture_decor and garden_tools have lower profit margins.

The average price of products in the health_beauty category are significantly higher than the competition while garden_tools and watches_gifts are moderately higher and computers_accessories and furniture_decor are lower.

There are not enough data points to determine price elasticity for each product with a high degree of confidence but but we did get statistically significant results for the following:

Recommendations¶
  1. health3 and health6 have a high price elasticity of 25.58 and 18.93 respectively. These products have sold higher quantities at higher prices, the category itself has a high market demand but the company has relatively low market share. I recommend experimenting with slightly higher prices for these products and monitor the results. If increasing prices results in higher sales or at least on par with current sales, I would recommend testing out higher prices for other products in the same category that did not have statistically significant price elasticities but might be perceived as a "premium" product. From a visual look at the "Quantity vs Unit Price by Product ID and Product Category" chart, health2 and health8 could be good candidates to experiment with.

  2. garden2 has a price elasticity of 7.48 and is part of a category that has a high market demand but low market share. I would recommend experimenting with slightly higher prices for this product and monitoring the results.

  3. watches1, watches7 and garden1 have moderately low negative price elasticities. These products have a high market demand but low market share. watches7 has a product score that is 0.3 lower than the competitor average. The average price of products in the watches and garden tools categories are also higher than the competition. I would recommend experimenting with slightly lower prices for these products and monitor the results to see if the increased demand results in higher total profit.

If we take a closer look at garden1 for example, the average product price for the company is $105.76 with a average profit margin of 63.21%. The total average profit per sale would be $66.85. The average monthly sales have been 8.2 units translating to $548.18 in monthly profit. <br><br> If we were to decrease the price by 10% ($95.18), the demand should increase by 41.3% (11.6 units). The total profit per sale would be $56.68 (95.18 - 38.50). If we were to assume monthly sales to increase to 11.6 units, that would amount to $657.49 in monthly profit which is higher than the current monthly profit of $548.18.

4. furniture2 is the company's top selling product by units sold. Although this category doesn't have the same market demand as the other top selling categories, there is likely some potential to increase the market share. I would recommend experimenting with slightly lower prices for this product and monitoring the results.

Next Steps¶
  1. If the above recommendations prove to be fruitful, we can experiment with the other products on the price_elasticity_df. Furthermore, as more data is collected, we can update the price_elasticity_df to see if we get more statistically significant results.

  2. The actual cost of goods was not provided in this dataset. I would recommend including those costs in the future to determine the true profit margin of each product.

  3. There are other variables from the dataset that were not investigated such as lag_price, seasonality and number of photos available on the listing. Lag price could be investigated to see if the the previous month's price has an effect on the current month's price. Seasonality could be investigated to optimize prices based on the season. Number of photos available on the listing could be investigated to see if including more photos has a relationship with increase sales.
